Scott: And then they discover it and you discover it together at the same time.

807
00:51:16,900 --> 00:51:22,132
Scott: And it's sort of you're zooming out and, you know, it's not like a terrible secret of space.

808
00:51:22,212 --> 00:51:22,733
Scott: where it's like.

809
00:51:23,194 --> 00:51:25,980
Scott: we're telling you there's a terrible secret of space, but we're not telling you the answers.

810
00:51:25,980 --> 00:51:27,264
Scott: You're always asking questions.

811
00:51:27,685 --> 00:51:32,840
Scott: It's that you're watching a thing and then suddenly there are answers you didn't even have questions for.

812
00:51:33,280 --> 00:51:33,341
Rym: Yup.

813
00:51:33,361 --> 00:51:34,605
Rym: I think your analogy was right.

814
00:51:34,665 --> 00:51:38,880
Rym: It's like the show, like the camera is just slowly zooming further and further out.

815
00:51:39,260 --> 00:51:40,787
Rym: And bit by bit, things come into frame.

816
00:51:40,807 --> 00:51:43,320
Rym: You're like, wait, what the fuck is going on over there?

817
00:51:45,521 --> 00:51:48,773
Scott: It's like you see a puppet and you think it's real and then you zoom out.

818
00:51:48,833 --> 00:51:50,419
Scott: It's like, oh, there was a puppet master.

819
00:51:50,720 --> 00:51:53,634
Scott: And then you zoom out and the puppet master was also a puppet.

820
00:51:53,674 --> 00:51:54,619
Scott: Daddy three puppets.

821
00:51:54,880 --> 00:51:57,328
Rym: But what I also appreciated was the way it starts.

822
00:51:57,429 --> 00:52:00,057
Rym: Like in the first episode, it's not really a spoiler.

823
00:52:00,078 --> 00:52:00,800
Rym: It's the first episode.

824
00:52:01,040 --> 00:52:12,820
Rym: But the show I thought was going to be a lot less good than it was because in the first episode it starts with this like really pedestrian con and the guy doesn't work out and it just feels really predictable.

825
00:52:13,520 --> 00:52:20,980
Rym: But then when Ed and Murrah, like the main character, sort of slides in and you see what the real con was, I didn't expect that and it was clever.

826
00:52:21,582 --> 00:52:23,138
Rym: And then the show just escalates from there.

827
00:52:24,101 --> 00:52:24,703
Scott: All right.

828
00:52:24,723 --> 00:52:27,150
Scott: So let's talk about, there's a few details in the show I want to touch on.

829
00:52:27,171 --> 00:52:30,060
Scott: So the first detail is the background art, right?

830
00:52:30,421 --> 00:52:32,318
Rym: That background art is fucking amazing.

831
00:52:33,140 --> 00:52:37,660
Scott: I don't know the name of the art style or the artist who drew that way.

832
00:52:37,920 --> 00:52:41,439
Rym: It's like abstract and hyper saturated and colorful.

833
00:52:42,481 --> 00:52:44,405
Scott: It's a style you've seen before.

834
00:52:44,525 --> 00:52:51,180
Scott: It's like you could imagine that even though the show takes each of the different episode, the, what's it called?

835
00:52:51,521 --> 00:52:52,703
Scott: The arcs or whatever.

836
00:52:53,284 --> 00:52:54,045
Scott: The arcs, right?

837
00:52:54,126 --> 00:52:55,829
Scott: Take place in different geographies.

838
00:52:55,989 --> 00:53:01,580
Scott: One of them's in Singapore, one of them's in the UK, I think, or France.

839
00:53:01,660 --> 00:53:03,378
Rym: I guess it's a spoiler to say where the last one is.

840
00:53:04,482 --> 00:53:07,020
Scott: Yeah, but all four of them are in different locations.

841
00:53:08,921 --> 00:53:17,820
Scott: The first one is in California, but they all feel like a painting that you would see hanging in like a motel in California in your hotel room, right?

842
00:53:18,221 --> 00:53:19,263
Scott: And it's like a style.

843
00:53:19,363 --> 00:53:29,100
Scott: I've seen that style before, but I'm not, I don't know enough about art history or what to Google for to figure out the name of that style or the artist who came up with that style.

844
00:53:29,140 --> 00:53:30,206
Scott: But I've seen that style.

845
00:53:30,447 --> 00:53:32,940
Scott: It's a style I like, you don't see it that often.

846
00:53:33,441 --> 00:53:42,400
Scott: And they, every single background, whether it's like a shot where the background is taking up most of the frame or just like a regular old talking headshot.

847
00:53:42,941 --> 00:53:48,955
Scott: It's like almost always the background is a painting in that style, right?

848
00:53:49,015 --> 00:53:50,960
Scott: With quite a bit of effort put into it.

849
00:53:51,080 --> 00:54:00,897
Scott: And it's really, you know, it sort of maintains, no matter what's happening in the show, that sort of, you know, sort of visual like anchor point, right?

850
00:54:01,137 --> 00:54:02,700
Scott: Of stylistically.

851
00:54:02,940 --> 00:54:11,220
Rym: And it subtly really sets the mood for the scenes and sets the mood for how apart from non-con men these characters are.

852
00:54:11,881 --> 00:54:14,727
Rym: And also it really like pegs them to the place they're in.

853
00:54:14,807 --> 00:54:21,560
Rym: Like the Singapore arc is like specifically and directly set in a very specific part of Singapore.

854
00:54:21,960 --> 00:54:23,524
Rym: The LA one is like a real place.

855
00:54:23,544 --> 00:54:24,687
Rym: Like they scouted locations.

856
00:54:24,707 --> 00:54:29,800
Rym: They made it very, very true to the spirit of those places, but highly stylized.

857
00:54:29,880 --> 00:54:32,625
Scott: It's not one of those ones where it's like, you know, it's New York, but no, it's not.

858
00:54:32,685 --> 00:54:33,546
Scott: It's not New York.

859
00:54:33,647 --> 00:54:34,528
Scott: It's like, oh yeah, that's...

860
00:54:42,101 --> 00:54:55,260
Rym: It has that history of like where you've been and I've been there more than I've realized, but it really captures what Singapore feels like if you're there and you're well off and like in the kind of places that they're at.

861
00:54:55,460 --> 00:54:58,705
Rym: Not like daily life, but like this larger than life experience.

862
00:55:01,409 --> 00:55:09,340
Rym: The other thing I would say is that the soundtrack, I feel like it is like directly trying to pay some homage to Cowboy Bebop, like straight up.

863
00:55:11,001 --> 00:55:13,829
Scott: It's not the kind of soundtrack that I would put on, right?

864
00:55:13,849 --> 00:55:17,780
Scott: Like I would play, but it's, while you're watching it, it's a lot of fun.

865
00:55:17,940 --> 00:55:24,855
Rym: It's one of those, it fits, but it's not a score that's particularly memorable other than of course the closer, but that's not a score.

866
00:55:24,916 --> 00:55:26,860
Rym: That's a soundtrack and it's just a Freddie Mercury song.

867
00:55:27,820 --> 00:55:28,061
Scott: Right.

868
00:55:28,362 --> 00:55:29,645
Scott: We already know that song.

869
00:55:30,346 --> 00:55:36,000
Scott: Another thing I want to point out is that, you know, you have this main character who is a Japanese guy, right?

870
00:55:36,902 --> 00:55:43,336
Scott: And his name is Edamura and people, a lot of the characters make fun of him and call him Edamame, right?

871
00:55:43,356 --> 00:55:45,340
Scott: Which is, you know, the green peas.

872
00:55:45,540 --> 00:55:54,320
Rym: Because the show is very specifically like he is a Japanese character out in the world among mostly non-Japanese people and people make fun of him for it.

873
00:55:55,480 --> 00:55:55,761
Scott: Yeah.

874
00:55:55,821 --> 00:56:04,260
Scott: There's like a cultural sensitivity aspect to it, especially since even though these characters are traveling all around the world, right?

875
00:56:04,360 --> 00:56:08,940
Scott: You're watching this show either in Japanese with English subtitles or with an English dub.

876
00:56:09,920 --> 00:56:16,360
Scott: And so the characters will be mostly speaking in the language that you wonder that you choose for your audio track.

877
00:56:17,122 --> 00:56:22,453
Scott: But it's sort of assumed that like while they're in France, right?

878
00:56:22,553 --> 00:56:25,800
Scott: It's like, okay, that character doesn't speak French, but all these other ones do.

879
00:56:26,100 --> 00:56:32,100
Scott: And it's like, you know, sometimes they'll actually speak French with subtitles.

880
00:56:32,400 --> 00:56:33,102
Rym: I love that.

881
00:56:33,202 --> 00:56:34,386
Rym: I almost feel like it was a gag on them.

882
00:56:34,426 --> 00:56:39,300
Rym: They made the voice actors speak English and French a bunch in this show as well.

883
00:56:40,001 --> 00:56:44,167
Scott: But then there'll be times where like, okay, I watched the Japanese English subtitles.

884
00:56:44,228 --> 00:56:52,100
Scott: There are scenes where characters are talking in Japanese, but it's just assumed they're actually talking in English because you're in California right now.

885
00:56:52,720 --> 00:56:52,820
Scott: Right.

886
00:56:52,880 --> 00:57:01,019
Scott: Because they'll make comments like your accent, you know, everyone, you know, your English accent is kind of no good, even though the character didn't speak in English at all just then.

887
00:57:02,841 --> 00:57:09,118
Scott: So there's this sort of this and all the it's clearly it's very clear which characters are like, that's a French character, right?

888
00:57:09,138 --> 00:57:09,860
Scott: That's a Middle Eastern character.

889
00:57:09,860 --> 00:57:18,860
Rym: But they play it up and like there's in the first few episodes, there are long scenes of all the characters like speaking in English, even in the Japanese soundtrack or the Japanese audio.

890
00:57:19,421 --> 00:57:19,521
Scott: Yeah.

891
00:57:19,561 --> 00:57:20,363
Scott: They're all con artists.

892
00:57:20,383 --> 00:57:27,320
Scott: So they all they're all fluent in many languages and can even, you know, hide their accents or not have accents in various languages to some degree.

893
00:57:27,420 --> 00:57:29,984
Scott: But it's clear.

894
00:57:30,024 --> 00:57:39,660
Scott: the main character's Japanese accent, you know, doesn't, you know, he has it when he speaks in English where like one of the other characters, you know, is French.

895
00:57:39,760 --> 00:57:42,769
Scott: But if they speak English, you wouldn't know that they're French because they're so good.

896
00:57:42,809 --> 00:57:43,631
Scott: They're a con artist.

897
00:57:43,651 --> 00:57:45,295
Scott: They've learned to speak without an accent.

898
00:57:45,336 --> 00:57:46,840
Scott: and how many different languages, you know.

899
00:57:47,780 --> 00:57:52,608
Rym: Another thing I could say is that I like the like, for example, the first arc, which is kind of set in

900
00:57:52,728 --> 00:57:53,008
Rym: L.A.,

901
00:57:53,549 --> 00:58:00,880
Rym: it definitely has a big get shorty vibe, like the way that who that director is, who's also in the mob and like what's going on.

902
00:58:01,361 --> 00:58:08,299
Rym: And there's a scene that is clearly an homage to that scene in The Untouchables where Al Capone beats the shit out of a guy with a baseball bat.

903
00:58:08,881 --> 00:58:10,022
Rym: But we're watching.

904
00:58:10,082 --> 00:58:12,266
Rym: I'm thinking, oh, they're going to do the Al Capone thing.

905
00:58:12,666 --> 00:58:22,040
Rym: But the director guy, who is the mob boss guy, is such a basic piece of shit that he basically is like, I'm doing the Capone thing.

906
00:58:22,160 --> 00:58:24,346
Rym: And then he does the Capone thing like that.

907
00:58:24,767 --> 00:58:27,935
Rym: Like it's almost like he's almost you'll have to see it to see what I mean.

908
00:58:27,955 --> 00:58:29,259
Rym: Like that guy is such a doofus.

909
00:58:30,165 --> 00:58:31,054
Scott: Yep, yep, yep.

910
00:58:33,361 --> 00:58:40,817
Rym: In terms of like we're not going to spoil anything about the end, but I'd say the end is pretty satisfying with a possible off note.

911
00:58:41,197 --> 00:58:42,340
Rym: I see what they were going for.

912
00:58:42,960 --> 00:58:48,959
Rym: There's sort of a post ending, very short scene that might radically change how you interpret the show.

913
00:58:49,908 --> 00:58:50,659
Scott: Hmm, that's true.

914
00:58:52,721 --> 00:58:56,887
Scott: But yeah, I think it's not just the post scene, but also the ending.

915
00:58:57,508 --> 00:59:05,720
Scott: On the one hand, the ending does sort of tie up and explain everything with like the most zoomed out biggest explanation, right?

916
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:14,297
Rym: Like at the end of the show, it's almost like I had a checklist of they better not just ignore the child trafficking that was happening in that arc.

917
00:59:14,677 --> 00:59:16,000
Rym: And like every box got checked.

918
00:59:16,961 --> 00:59:19,906
Scott: Yeah, they just took everything that they had and just like wrapped it up.

919
00:59:19,986 --> 00:59:24,334
Scott: But I think the ending was it felt at least whether it was rushed or not.

920
00:59:24,394 --> 00:59:28,000
Scott: production wise, it's the pace of it is rushed.

921
00:59:28,240 --> 00:59:31,327
Scott: It's like the things that happen at the end happened so quickly.

922
00:59:31,467 --> 00:59:34,293
Scott: It's like, you know, this and then this and then this and then this.

923
00:59:34,353 --> 00:59:37,360
Scott: It's like they're just like cramming that ending full of everything.

924
00:59:37,520 --> 00:59:43,760
Rym: I felt like they could have either cut a little bit of that out or had like a few more episodes to make that all come together.

925
00:59:44,442 --> 00:59:44,622
Scott: Yeah.

926
00:59:44,722 --> 00:59:52,080
Scott: And the other thing is that it becomes because of that rapid pace of the ending, it's a little like confusing and messy, right?

927
00:59:52,340 --> 00:59:54,100
Rym: But at the same time, that almost works.

928
00:59:55,060 --> 01:00:00,527
Scott: You get the information about how a thing was wrapped up and all the facts and all the questions are answered.

929
01:00:00,948 --> 01:00:10,060
Scott: But it's like you could have spent a little more time showing those answers in a more emotionally impactful fashion, right?

930
01:00:10,160 --> 01:00:22,480
Rym: Though at least I can say that one thing that did do is that when we were watching it and the sort of final arc, like the con that's happening gets revealed and some people walk out a door after the floor thing happens.

931
01:00:22,600 --> 01:00:23,822
Rym: I'm being very vague here on purpose.

932
01:00:25,125 --> 01:00:27,970
Rym: We were both just sitting here thinking, what the fuck?

933
01:00:28,291 --> 01:00:30,094
Rym: Does this show get weird now?

934
01:00:30,195 --> 01:00:32,980
Rym: Is this supernatural or magic or nonsense?

935
01:00:33,461 --> 01:00:34,723
Rym: Because we almost got conned.

936
01:00:34,783 --> 01:00:36,065
Rym: Like we were conned ourselves.

937
01:00:36,486 --> 01:00:43,238
Rym: And then as the camera zooms out and it's like, oh, oh, like you have this moment of I get it.

938
01:00:43,338 --> 01:00:44,440
Rym: I get what they did.

939
01:00:45,300 --> 01:00:45,381
Scott: Yeah.

940
01:00:45,923 --> 01:00:46,104
Rym: Yeah.

941
01:00:46,124 --> 01:00:49,120
Rym: And I feel like that was done well, but it could have been done slightly better.

942
01:00:49,861 --> 01:00:50,041
Scott: Yeah.

943
01:00:50,141 --> 01:00:57,020
Scott: Like I was saying before, how it's a show that's giving you answers without, you know, asking, you know, giving you the question.

944
01:00:57,340 --> 01:00:58,708
Rym: That's the first time I gave you a question.

945
01:00:58,889 --> 01:01:00,860
Rym: I was literally like, what the fuck just happened?

946
01:01:01,421 --> 01:01:02,824
Scott: But it's sort of in that way.

947
01:01:02,944 --> 01:01:04,127
Scott: It's conning you, right?

948
01:01:04,227 --> 01:01:09,959
Scott: It's like you're rather than you knowing there's a terrible secret of space and just not knowing what it is.

949
01:01:09,979 --> 01:01:10,260
Scott: Right.

950
01:01:10,300 --> 01:01:12,485
Scott: It's like, I know there's a mystery out there.

951
01:01:12,566 --> 01:01:15,673
Scott: It's like, it's like, no, there is no mystery.

952
01:01:15,754 --> 01:01:16,495
Scott: This is the truth.

953
01:01:16,576 --> 01:01:17,478
Scott: This is what's happening.

954
01:01:17,498 --> 01:01:18,320
Scott: We're showing you everything.

955
01:01:18,380 --> 01:01:21,026
Scott: Look, we're showing you that they're con men and that they're pulling a con.

956
01:01:21,086 --> 01:01:22,710
Scott: You see the whole con, right?

957
01:01:23,150 --> 01:01:27,520
Scott: You see everything, but you're being, you yourself are being conned, right?

958
01:01:27,901 --> 01:01:31,750
Scott: As the larger con is revealed to you and characters simultaneously.

959
01:01:31,770 --> 01:01:33,354
Scott: Right.

960
01:01:33,374 --> 01:01:36,020
Scott: So that's what I think gives it a little different structure.

961
01:01:36,620 --> 01:01:46,780
Rym: Another thing, something actually I did appreciate around like the way the show progressed too, is that the characters were pretty complex and many of them had significant changes like over the course of the show for as short as it was.

962
01:01:47,521 --> 01:02:05,540
Rym: But also I didn't know where the show was going until the final arc because there are a lot of moments where the show looks like it's about to take a very dark turn and it doesn't necessarily reassure you of, no, it's not actually going to go too far down that road.

963
01:02:05,921 --> 01:02:09,347
Rym: It almost feels like it's at any moment it could get real dark.

964
01:02:09,868 --> 01:02:16,920
Rym: Like there's a moment where a character kind of out of nowhere pulls a knife and you don't see it coming and an episode ends.

965
01:02:17,680 --> 01:02:23,020
Rym: And I like, I give it a 50/50 shot that the show is about to take a really dark swerve.

966
01:02:23,781 --> 01:02:23,901
Scott: Right?

967
01:02:23,921 --> 01:02:27,227
Scott: It's like there are dark things that happen in the show for real, right?

968
01:02:27,848 --> 01:02:34,300
Scott: And the characters, while they're always, you know, when they're not conning someone and acting, right, to con people.

969
01:02:34,860 --> 01:02:45,960
Scott: They are always, all of them, even if they all have dark pasts to varying degrees, they all act in sort of a jovial having a good time joking around manner with each other.

970
01:02:45,960 --> 01:02:47,087
Rym: Well, you know how to sum that up?

971
01:02:47,610 --> 01:02:49,160
Rym: There's a meta message in this show.

972
01:02:49,500 --> 01:02:50,760
Scott: Teasing each other, right?

973
01:02:50,980 --> 01:02:54,337
Rym: The meta message of this show is it's all fun and games until it isn't.

974
01:02:55,440 --> 01:02:55,881
Scott: Right.

975
01:02:55,901 --> 01:03:06,180
Scott: And then at the same time though, they always will, even though they're almost always just joking around with each other, they'll always stop and say like, no, we're not teammates, right?

976
01:03:06,760 --> 01:03:09,145
Scott: You could just, yeah, you could just die.

977
01:03:09,185 --> 01:03:10,708
Scott: We're doing dangerous shit.

978
01:03:10,728 --> 01:03:13,274
Scott: And they absolutely, and they absolutely are, right?

979
01:03:13,354 --> 01:03:15,679
Scott: So, and they're also reminding you, the viewers.

980
01:03:16,520 --> 01:03:30,600
Scott: So then when dangerous shit happens, sometimes it's real and sometimes it's a con and you can't tell until later when it's revealed whether that was, you know, a fake or real dangerous things that happened.

981
01:03:31,281 --> 01:03:46,520
Rym: Which is because some con movies or con like confidence shows, they tend to portray thieves who don't suffer consequences and also seem to feel like they are immune to consequences.

982
01:03:46,740 --> 01:03:56,080
Rym: Like it's always assumed everything's going to work, but the show definitely edges into talking about how that is a fiction and how real cod art is doing these kinds of things.

983
01:03:56,180 --> 01:04:00,340
Rym: Like they are moments from death, basically constantly with what they're actually doing.

984
01:04:01,320 --> 01:04:01,400
Scott: Yeah.

985
01:04:01,420 --> 01:04:04,627
Scott: And there's, there's plenty of scenes where while they're executing a con, right?

986
01:04:04,647 --> 01:04:08,735
Scott: There's, they're building tension showing you like how close they are to messing it up.

987
01:04:08,776 --> 01:04:10,860
Scott: Like, Oh, security, you know, they were trying to do something.

988
01:04:11,501 --> 01:04:14,327
Scott: A security guard, you know, is coming back, right?

989
01:04:14,548 --> 01:04:19,880
Scott: He's going off the plan and they had to, they have to think fast and come up with, do something else.

990
01:04:19,920 --> 01:04:20,020
Scott: Right?

991
01:04:20,080 --> 01:04:20,822
Scott: What are they going to do?

992
01:04:20,862 --> 01:04:21,683
Scott: Are they going to mess up?

993
01:04:21,743 --> 01:04:23,987
Scott: Are they, you know, they were trying to escape.

994
01:04:24,027 --> 01:04:24,708
Scott: They didn't escape.

995
01:04:24,728 --> 01:04:27,373
Scott: Uh, you know, all these different things happen.

996
01:04:27,393 --> 01:04:29,416
Scott: They, they, they wanted to convince someone of something.

997
01:04:29,436 --> 01:04:30,478
Scott: They failed to convince them.

998
01:04:30,518 --> 01:04:31,360
Scott: Well, now what do they do?

999
01:04:33,201 --> 01:04:48,080
Scott: And it's like, you can't tell if sometimes because there are cons within cons, if the failure to convince was part of the plan or they've just successfully adapted to the plan or if the plan has failed and now they don't know what to do and they got to find a way to work it out later.

1000
01:04:49,121 --> 01:04:49,381
Rym: Yeah.

1001
01:04:50,442 --> 01:04:53,246
Scott: Do they have the, all these layers planned out in advance or not?

1002
01:04:53,927 --> 01:04:59,555
Scott: You're always, you don't really know because it's not like they sat you down and told you what the whole con was going to be before they executed it.

1003
01:04:59,575 --> 01:05:03,580
Scott: You're just watching this execution, not knowing who planned what at what level.

1004
01:05:03,680 --> 01:05:11,200
Rym: Which is extra fun because for the first three arcs, Edamura, our main character, he is in just as much in the dark as you, the viewer are.

1005
01:05:11,562 --> 01:05:14,660
Scott: I think in all the four arcs, you basically know what Edamura knows.

1006
01:05:14,680 --> 01:05:16,063
Scott: Well, the fourth arc is interesting.

1007
01:05:16,083 --> 01:05:24,339
Rym: It would always be a spoiler to make my argument about this, but I think the fourth arc is where that's the only time he knows what is going on.

1008
01:05:25,261 --> 01:05:25,383
Scott: Yeah.

1009
01:05:25,424 --> 01:05:26,620
Scott: He knows more in that one for sure.

1010
01:05:26,982 --> 01:05:27,226
Rym: Yeah.

1011
01:05:27,246 --> 01:05:28,059
Rym: Cause that the final.

1012
01:05:29,121 --> 01:05:31,239
Scott: Sometimes I guess in that one, sometimes he knows more than you.

1013
01:05:31,700 --> 01:05:31,901
Scott: Yeah.

1014
01:05:32,181 --> 01:05:38,439
Rym: I guess in the final one, one way to put it is the first three arcs are almost training and the fourth arc is he does the thing.

1015
01:05:39,463 --> 01:05:39,625
Scott: Mm hmm.

1016
01:05:39,828 --> 01:05:39,969
Scott: Mm hmm.

1017
01:05:40,152 --> 01:05:40,577
Scott: Pretty much.

1018
01:05:40,597 --> 01:05:40,699
Scott: Yeah.

1019
01:05:41,101 --> 01:05:43,247
Rym: But yeah, I think we'll talk a little bit about spoilers.

1020
01:05:43,287 --> 01:05:47,760
Rym: So the last thing I'll just say is this show, like this is an anime, if you like anime, watch it.

1021
01:05:48,020 --> 01:05:49,528
Rym: Like this is a fine anime.

1022
01:05:49,548 --> 01:05:51,276
Rym: It's one of the better ones to come out in a long time.

1023
01:05:51,336 --> 01:05:52,120
Scott: It's just on Netflix.

1024
01:05:52,640 --> 01:05:58,477
Scott: I wouldn't subscribe to Netflix to watch this show, but if you have Netflix and you like animation, why wouldn't you watch this show?

1025
01:05:58,577 --> 01:05:59,440
Scott: It doesn't take that long.

1026
01:05:59,520 --> 01:06:04,280
Rym: This is the kind of show, if we showed the first four episodes at like an RIT anime club, like the people would be cheering.

1027
01:06:05,061 --> 01:06:11,740
Rym: It's the kind of show that like people would show up to the marathon, but like it's not a cowboy bebop, but it's a B plus.

1028
01:06:12,600 --> 01:06:17,199
Rym: I think it could have been like a full on a minus if the ending had been a little bit tighter.

1029
01:06:19,380 --> 01:06:21,143
Rym: Didn't really hit a, but it did do.

1030
01:06:21,183 --> 01:06:32,120
Rym: a lot of the things that good shows do like the closing, like the closing animation, what's happening on screen with the cats and like the lyrics of the song together are allegory for what happens in the show.

1031
01:06:33,201 --> 01:06:33,742
Scott: Yeah, that's true.

1032
01:06:33,782 --> 01:06:35,287
Rym: That's one of the things we always talk about.

1033
01:06:35,688 --> 01:06:39,880
Rym: Anime where you can figure out things in the show from the openers and closers tend to be better shows.

1034
01:06:42,260 --> 01:06:43,906
Rym: So spoilers, we're going to spoil stuff.

1035
01:06:43,926 --> 01:06:47,600
Rym: If you haven't watched the show, stop listening because we're going to spoil stuff in a show.

1036
01:06:47,880 --> 01:06:54,140
Scott: Or if you're like me and you don't believe in that spoilers ruin spoil things and that's something that can be spoiled isn't, you know, worth watching at all.

1037
01:06:55,161 --> 01:07:00,593
Rym: But from this point, not only are we going to spoil things, but we're going to assume you've seen it and not explain what we're talking about.

1038
01:07:00,634 --> 01:07:03,360
Rym: Like we're going to talk about it like you have seen it with us.

1039
01:07:04,360 --> 01:07:07,180
Scott: Just out of common courtesy, we're just letting you know that's your choice.

1040
01:07:07,460 --> 01:07:08,382
Rym: Last chance spoilers.

1041
01:07:08,863 --> 01:07:18,220
Rym: My favorite thing at the end, like of all the things that happened in the end, I think the part I enjoyed the most, I was very happy that his wife was a hundred percent in on it the whole time.

1042
01:07:19,701 --> 01:07:22,806
Rym: That would have felt like a sour note if he had been hiding this life from her.

1043
01:07:23,387 --> 01:07:30,320
Rym: The fact that she knew and approved of it and was basically just like trying to set her son up to like survive and deal with it.

1044
01:07:31,160 --> 01:07:44,380
Scott: I just thought that's why she kept, well, she didn't want to, the thing is like, she didn't tell her son cause he told her not to, but she would just, but like she, you know, she didn't, you know, hate the dad even though, you know, supposedly.

1045
01:07:44,821 --> 01:07:51,996
Rym: I always got an undercurrent that she liked what he was doing and was probably even involved in some things when she was younger.

1046
01:07:52,156 --> 01:07:54,180
Rym: And then they might've changed that because they had Edamura.

1047
01:07:55,240 --> 01:07:55,577
Scott: Who knows?

1048
01:07:56,060 --> 01:08:01,440
Rym: But they don't, they don't go into so much detail on that, but they, the way they reveal that all those scenes I think were just very emotional and touching.

1049
01:08:02,760 --> 01:08:02,920
Scott: Yeah.

1050
01:08:03,061 --> 01:08:13,240
Scott: The thing that really got me was that you have the, right from the early parts of the show, you see the dad was a, you know, this good lawyer who, you know, got arrested for child trafficking.

1051
01:08:13,320 --> 01:08:13,581
Scott: Right.

1052
01:08:14,182 --> 01:08:20,694
Scott: And you know, from that point on, I just assumed, you know, like I didn't have questions about that.

1053
01:08:20,755 --> 01:08:21,636
Scott: Like where is dad?

1054
01:08:21,676 --> 01:08:23,500
Scott: I didn't think that was going to come up.

1055
01:08:23,819 --> 01:08:27,974
Rym: Around the third arc I started wondering like, what was really the deal with his dad?

1056
01:08:28,033 --> 01:08:29,680
Rym: Cause that was definitely going to be the fourth arc.

1057
01:08:30,580 --> 01:08:38,595
Scott: Well, cause I saw, well, yeah, but I basically, you know, from arc one, two, and most of three, I was just like, dad's in jail.

1058
01:08:38,615 --> 01:08:39,877
Scott: I had no questions about dad.

1059
01:08:39,917 --> 01:08:40,939
Scott: He was just a bad guy.

1060
01:08:40,999 --> 01:08:41,600
Scott: That's what happened.

1061
01:08:41,760 --> 01:08:46,212
Scott: I did not think for one second, the dad was like a part of the plot of the show.

1062
01:08:46,274 --> 01:08:48,319
Scott: I thought it was just like, he was part of the OG gang.

1063
01:08:49,240 --> 01:08:49,380
Scott: Right.

1064
01:08:49,399 --> 01:08:52,147
Scott: It's just, it's just like, that's the backstory of Edamura.

1065
01:08:52,207 --> 01:08:53,691
Scott: His dad was a guy who went to jail.

1066
01:08:53,731 --> 01:08:53,992
Scott: Right.

1067
01:08:54,332 --> 01:08:55,975
Scott: I didn't question where's dad now.

1068
01:08:56,337 --> 01:08:57,038
Scott: She's in a jail.

1069
01:08:57,059 --> 01:08:57,399
Scott: Right.

1070
01:08:58,580 --> 01:09:08,920
Rym: And the show, it did that thing I love where an episode just starts or like a long scene just starts in the past and you see like a history when you see the original gang.

1071
01:09:09,500 --> 01:09:15,129
Rym: And then the moment when she was like, all right, let's do one more score.

1072
01:09:15,488 --> 01:09:19,314
Rym: That is the same as saying I'm going in for a closer look.

1073
01:09:19,756 --> 01:09:22,160
Rym: That is the same as saying we're going to die.

1074
01:09:23,300 --> 01:09:23,901
Scott: Yup.

1075
01:09:24,902 --> 01:09:29,988
Scott: That's a, that's old cliche of like, okay, we've done all these, you know, we've climbed 10 mountains.

1076
01:09:30,109 --> 01:09:32,432
Rym: It's like, all right guys, one more and then we're retiring.

1077
01:09:33,313 --> 01:09:33,533
Scott: Right.

1078
01:09:33,594 --> 01:09:34,073
Scott: Exactly.

1079
01:09:34,094 --> 01:09:35,917
Scott: This is my last day before retirement.

1080
01:09:36,237 --> 01:09:38,420
Scott: It's like, well, you're going to die on this day, aren't you?

1081
01:09:38,520 --> 01:09:38,700
Scott: Yeah.

1082
01:09:38,740 --> 01:09:48,500
Rym: But it did also bring up this interesting meta point about how everyone other than her had a reason, like a life and a reason to do cons, like to support that life in some way.

1083
01:09:49,001 --> 01:09:53,191
Rym: Except her, she was the one who was conning because she loved it.

1084
01:09:53,231 --> 01:09:56,840
Rym: Like that was the con, the con was the end and the means.

1085
01:09:57,660 --> 01:09:58,764
Scott: And she just having a good time.

1086
01:09:58,904 --> 01:09:59,165
Scott: Yeah.

1087
01:09:59,446 --> 01:10:04,583
Scott: Like, you know, where other people might've had a good time as a side effect of, you know, But they had a real life to get back to.

1088
01:10:04,663 --> 01:10:07,370
Rym: And there were consequences for them, like that.

1089
01:10:07,450 --> 01:10:09,014
Rym: she didn't seem to care about as much.

1090
01:10:09,996 --> 01:10:11,179
Scott: No, no, not at all.

1091
01:10:13,221 --> 01:10:21,360
Rym: I, I feel like they tried to make the very end where, you know, she comes back as being ambiguous, the way she reacts when she sees the, there's two ways to read it.

1092
01:10:21,841 --> 01:10:30,294
Rym: Either if she survived, like simply, or she orchestrated that on purpose to get Laurent out of that life.

1093
01:10:30,374 --> 01:10:33,800
Rym: So she could keep criming without him, like having a problem.

1094
01:10:35,001 --> 01:10:39,529
Scott: Or, you know, there's also the, you know, and she realized everything worked out.

1095
01:10:39,549 --> 01:10:45,660
Scott: It's like, okay, if she's still alive, is she a, because they sort of made it ambiguous, right?

1096
01:10:45,740 --> 01:10:50,370
Scott: Does she a still not remember anything, which she really doesn't remember anything.

1097
01:10:50,390 --> 01:10:51,332
Scott: That's a possibility.

1098
01:10:51,753 --> 01:10:53,217
Scott: B she's a con artist.

1099
01:10:53,237 --> 01:10:54,720
Scott: She's pretending not to remember anything.

1100
01:10:55,220 --> 01:11:00,328
Rym: And if she's pretending then was that just, she survived and that's how she survived.

1101
01:11:00,608 --> 01:11:04,153
Rym: Or did she plan this thing failing all along?

1102
01:11:04,193 --> 01:11:08,600
Rym: Was she the mastermind of freeing Laurent from this life and from his affection to her?

1103
01:11:10,161 --> 01:11:20,060
Rym: And the, the, the way, like the intonation of the way she said the final line of the show when she saw that, that jewel really, I think they made that ambiguous specifically on purpose.

1104
01:11:22,482 --> 01:11:28,080
Rym: And I don't know, it's a, it's not a bad moment, but I think the show would have been fine if it didn't have that last little scene.

1105
01:11:28,863 --> 01:11:29,045
Scott: Yeah.

1106
01:11:29,065 --> 01:11:32,119
Rym: I think, you know, it was really- The interpretation of the show is cleaner without that.

1107
01:11:32,780 --> 01:11:32,941
Scott: Yeah.

1108
01:11:33,242 --> 01:11:37,940
Scott: I think up until that point, you had all these different scenarios where people were fake dying.

1109
01:11:38,981 --> 01:11:40,410
Rym: They almost overused that.

1110
01:11:40,470 --> 01:11:41,839
Rym: They basically gave Edinburgh PTSD.

1111
01:11:43,040 --> 01:11:43,240
Scott: Yeah.

1112
01:11:43,341 --> 01:11:49,751
Scott: They, they overuse quite a few things, you know, along those lines, but especially the fake dying.

1113
01:11:51,313 --> 01:11:55,400
Scott: And it's like, okay, you fake died and then, okay, you did it once.

1114
01:11:55,460 --> 01:11:56,403
Scott: And then it's like, oh, you fake it.

1115
01:11:56,423 --> 01:11:58,591
Scott: Then it's like, you believe it the next time.

1116
01:11:58,651 --> 01:12:01,220
Scott: Cause like you've already used the fake dying, right?

1117
01:12:01,641 --> 01:12:04,045
Scott: And it's like, no, they just keep using the fake dying.

1118
01:12:04,085 --> 01:12:05,968
Scott: Like nobody fucking died at all.

1119
01:12:06,008 --> 01:12:08,212
Scott: They just fake deaths like a hundred times.

1120
01:12:08,272 --> 01:12:12,620
Scott: And it's like, uh, after you've done it that many times.

1121
01:12:12,780 --> 01:12:13,081
Rym: I don't know.

1122
01:12:13,101 --> 01:12:16,454
Rym: The guy who got his testicles crushed by that baseball bat, he might not have survived.

1123
01:12:16,514 --> 01:12:16,915
Rym: We don't know.

1124
01:12:17,337 --> 01:12:18,100
Rym: We don't see him again.

1125
01:12:18,461 --> 01:12:23,592
Scott: But none of this, there are several times significant characters die and they're not really dead.

1126
01:12:23,632 --> 01:12:27,060
Scott: It's like, they just kept doing that over and over.

1127
01:12:27,400 --> 01:12:38,379
Scott: And it's, it's like they, they did it enough times that before the end of the show, like sometime in the middle of that last arc, I basically was like, well, I guess no one dies in this show.

1128
01:12:38,459 --> 01:12:38,980
Scott: And I was right.

1129
01:12:39,060 --> 01:12:41,246
Scott: And it's like, you used it too many times.

1130
01:12:41,306 --> 01:12:44,073
Scott: If you would have used it maybe two less times, you would have been better off.

1131
01:12:44,454 --> 01:12:46,459
Scott: Um, you know, like actually kill someone.

1132
01:12:46,479 --> 01:12:46,720
Scott: Come on.

1133
01:12:47,060 --> 01:12:53,589
Rym: But I guess one thing I did appreciate that's, that's adjacent to that is that the actual cons were really simple.

1134
01:12:53,829 --> 01:13:01,719
Rym: Like while there's all this accretion amount around it, the con was literally just a very simple, all right, now this guy has given us the money and we're gone.

1135
01:13:01,859 --> 01:13:02,179
Rym: It's over.

1136
01:13:04,380 --> 01:13:15,591
Scott: And also, even though the, the big, big con, right, it's like, yeah, they planned this big, big con, but like they weren't, they clearly weren't planning the details of each thing.

1137
01:13:16,232 --> 01:13:16,492
Scott: Right.

1138
01:13:16,892 --> 01:13:24,940
Scott: So like, especially with the art guy, it's like, they weren't, it's like, you know, the fact that they accidentally sold him an expensive thing was an act, right?

1139
01:13:25,380 --> 01:13:30,800
Rym: Arguably, Lawrence, it was implied that he might've set that up, but they don't actually reveal.

1140
01:13:31,683 --> 01:13:33,379
Scott: Oh, that he might've just put that painting there?

1141
01:13:33,460 --> 01:13:37,146
Rym: Yeah, I think that was heavily implied because remember he got him, he got him to stay there.

1142
01:13:37,166 --> 01:13:40,972
Rym: Uh, like it fits with everything else Lauren was doing the whole time.

1143
01:13:41,593 --> 01:13:45,840
Rym: One of my favorite scenes with Lauren is when he just imagined himself murdering that triad guy.

1144
01:13:47,841 --> 01:13:55,000
Rym: That, that was a, that whole scene was one of the tensest scenes in the show where he's playing Ma Zhang with the mob bosses.

1145
01:13:56,000 --> 01:13:56,181
Scott: Yep.

1146
01:13:57,402 --> 01:14:03,172
Scott: Uh, they're also, I guess the fun, you know, one thing that show had, uh, is fun side characters, right?

1147
01:14:03,252 --> 01:14:08,560
Rym: And they were very, the, the seductress and the old man are my two favorite characters in the show by far.

1148
01:14:08,580 --> 01:14:09,779
Scott: Well, also the mechanic guy.

1149
01:14:10,020 --> 01:14:16,840
Rym: Oh yeah, he was fun, but I don't know, the seductress and the old man together, like you could have a spinoff show of those two and it would be great.

1150
01:14:16,840 --> 01:14:17,360
Rym: Exactly.

1151
01:14:17,501 --> 01:14:21,684
Scott: They were the, the fun side character action and like they're there the whole time.

1152
01:14:21,704 --> 01:14:37,759
Scott: Um, like they're there from the beginning to the end and they show up rather, you know, I think they did a good balance compared to other shows, which either don't use their fun side characters enough and you're disappointed or overusing them to where it's like, yeah, those are just like, you know, side characters.

1153
01:14:37,779 --> 01:14:39,420
Scott: You shouldn't be having them all over the place.

1154
01:14:40,080 --> 01:14:41,039
Rym: They use them the right amount.

1155
01:14:41,821 --> 01:14:42,883
Scott: The right amount, I think.

1156
01:14:42,923 --> 01:14:43,204
Scott: Yeah.

1157
01:14:43,264 --> 01:14:45,228
Scott: Which, which made me like them a lot.

1158
01:14:45,288 --> 01:14:46,670
Scott: So that was, that was good.

1159
01:14:47,612 --> 01:14:51,700
Scott: Um, the bringing back of characters from the previous acts.

1160
01:14:51,760 --> 01:14:54,880
Rym: That was the primary sour note I had from the show.

1161
01:14:54,900 --> 01:14:56,462
Scott: It was a little, it was a little meh.

1162
01:15:11,282 --> 01:15:13,000
Scott: That sort of made sense.

1163
01:15:13,360 --> 01:15:14,810
Rym: Especially cause he wasn't evil.

1164
01:15:14,951 --> 01:15:16,160
Rym: He was just a playboy.

1165
01:15:16,520 --> 01:15:17,094
Scott: He wasn't a bad guy.

1166
01:15:17,176 --> 01:15:17,360
Scott: Right.

1167
01:15:17,820 --> 01:15:22,440
Rym: He was, he did some bad things, but he wasn't like actively aggressively bad like his shitty brother.

1168
01:15:23,220 --> 01:15:23,320
Scott: Right.

1169
01:15:23,340 --> 01:15:29,249
Scott: But this bringing back the, the villains from the first three arcs in the fourth arc, just for that brief moment.

1170
01:15:29,609 --> 01:15:29,829
Scott: Right.

1171
01:15:29,869 --> 01:15:35,497
Scott: And portraying them that way was like, uh, no, that doesn't work.

1172
01:15:35,517 --> 01:15:37,200
Scott: You should have just been done with them.

1173
01:15:37,540 --> 01:15:37,761
Scott: Yep.

1174
01:15:37,821 --> 01:15:40,727
Rym: Just leave them be the whole, I thought you got revenge on them.

1175
01:15:40,747 --> 01:15:40,827
Rym: Yeah.

1176
01:15:41,809 --> 01:15:44,675
Rym: And also your gang is doing crime for all these other reasons.

1177
01:15:44,735 --> 01:15:46,679
Rym: They're just like selling meth to kids.

1178
01:15:46,779 --> 01:15:47,140
Rym: Like what?

1179
01:15:48,100 --> 01:15:48,341
Scott: Yeah.

1180
01:15:48,381 --> 01:15:49,304
Scott: Why do you do it?

1181
01:15:49,345 --> 01:15:49,485
Scott: Right?

1182
01:15:49,505 --> 01:15:50,549
Scott: Those are actual criminals.

1183
01:15:50,589 --> 01:15:51,191
Scott: They're bad guys.

1184
01:15:51,231 --> 01:15:52,817
Scott: That's why you conned them in the first place.

1185
01:15:52,837 --> 01:15:53,680
Scott: What the hell are you just doing?

1186
01:15:54,020 --> 01:16:02,957
Rym: For a brief moment, I had hoped that they were all actually being conned and they were going to be like abandoned on a boat or like something was going to happen to them, but no, no consequences for them.

1187
01:16:03,458 --> 01:16:04,260
Rym: That just got ignored.

1188
01:16:05,460 --> 01:16:14,012
Rym: That was honestly my only real sour note because while the fake deaths was a little bit overdone, it sort of made sense as con artists using the tools they have that work.

1189
01:16:14,773 --> 01:16:19,980
Rym: And they did play pretty well how Edamura was deeply traumatized by that.

1190
01:16:20,100 --> 01:16:21,283
Rym: And they all tried to brush it off.

1191
01:16:21,343 --> 01:16:27,759
Rym: And I thought it was interesting how Abby of all people was like, you guys are really underestimating Edamura and how much you fucked him up.

1192
01:16:29,641 --> 01:16:36,470
Scott: Well, especially I think the thing is that Edamura wasn't as much pre fucked up as the other people were.

1193
01:16:36,510 --> 01:16:41,897
Scott: The other people had more serious traumatic events in their past already.

1194
01:16:41,917 --> 01:16:43,860
Scott: Well, also they were older, I guess some of them.

1195
01:16:44,640 --> 01:16:51,980
Scott: And I guess the younger one, Abby, it's like her past was at war, the most serious darkest past of everybody.

1196
01:16:52,120 --> 01:17:00,340
Rym: Just that moment when she's pushing the guy's wheelchair, then she stops and you just hear the knife and she's like, tell me, did you pilot bombers during the Iraq war?

1197
01:17:01,120 --> 01:17:01,661
Scott: Exactly.

1198
01:17:01,721 --> 01:17:01,941
Scott: Right.

1199
01:17:02,001 --> 01:17:05,225
Scott: But her, uh, Edamura's past is.

